az wsp\u00f3lnego wychodzenia z domu. Rz\u0105d zaostrza kwarantann\u0119 |trans-title = Going out together from home is forbidden. The government tightens quarantine<!-- trans-title is the English translation --> | date= 2020-03-31 |newspaper= [[Newsweek|Newsweek Polska]] | url= https://www.newsweek.pl/wiedza/zdrowie/koronawirus-w-polsce-31-marca-ograniczenia-zakaz-wychodzenia-z-domu-zaostrzony/xr1qgc9 |accessdate=2020-03-31 |archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20200331112549/https://www.newsweek.pl/wiedza/zdrowie/koronawirus-w-polsce-31-marca-ograniczenia-zakaz-wychodzenia-z-domu-zaostrzony/xr1qgc9 |archivedate= 2020-03-31 |url-status=live <!-- live|dead|unfit|usurped --> |url-access = <!-- (subscription/registration/limited) default=free -->}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"OKOpress_rozporzadzenie1April2020\">{{cite news | last1=Ja\u0142oszewski | first1= Mariusz | language =pl | title= Rz\u0105d zaostrza izolacj\u0119: m\u0142odzie\u017c ma by\u0107 w domach, zakaz spacer\u00f3w w parkach [ograniczenia w punktach] |trans-title = The government tightens the lockdown: youth at home, walks in the park forbidden [list of restrictions]<!-- trans-title is the English translation --> | date= 2020-03-31 |newspaper= [[OKO.press]] | url= https://oko.press/rzad-zaostrza-izolacje/ |accessdate= 2020-03-31 |archiveurl= https://archive.today/50yFu |archivedate= 2020-03-31 |url-status=live <!-- live|dead|unfit|usurped --> |url-access = <!-- (subscription/registration/limited) default=free -->}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{commons category-inline|COVID-19 pandemic in Poland}}\n* [https://www.gov.pl/web/zdrowie Ministerstwo Zdrowia - Portal Gov.pl] ([[Ministry of Health (Poland)|Ministry of Health]])\n* [https://gis.gov.pl/kategoria/aktualnosci Aktualno\u015bci] ({{ill|G\u0142\u00f3wny Inspektorat Sanitarny|pl}} (GIS), national health agency)\n* [https://tvn24.pl/polska/koronawirus-w-polsce-kwarantanna-izolacja-nadzor-epidemiologiczny-czym-sie-roznia-4298999 informal and formal definitions of \"isolation\", \"quarantine\" and \"monitoring\"] (in Polish)\n* [https://www.gov.pl/web/koronawirus/wykaz-zarazen-koronawirusem-sars-cov-2 Polish government list of SARS-CoV-2 infections]\n* {{cite news|title = Koronawirus - wyleczeni |url = https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1IkXPT1r1R81tm4nLS7J4u-2rAIgi4QzPvVubJc-Jk2c/edit#gid=0|date = 30 March 2020|website= Google Docs |archiveurl= https://archive.today/Irjtc|url-status=live |archivedate = 30 March 2020}}\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|Poland]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Europe|Poland]]\n[[Category:2020 in Poland]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in Poland]]\n", "name_user": "Natanieluz", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Poland"}
{"title_page": "Jacobin (magazine)", "text_new": "{{redirect|Catalyst (journal)|the Australian publication|Catalyst (magazine)}}\n{{Infobox magazine\n| title = Jacobin\n| image_file = File:Jacobin fall 2013 cover.jpg\n| image_size = 225px\n| image_caption = Issue 11/12 (fall 2013)\n| editor = [[Bhaskar Sunkara]]\n| editor_title = Publisher\n| paid_circulation = 40,000<ref name=\"circulation\">{{cite news |last1=Baird |first1=Robert |title=The ABCs of Jacobin |url=https://www.cjr.org/special_report/the-abcs-of-jacobin-socialist-magazine.php |accessdate=8 September 2019 |work=Columbia Journalism Review |language=en}}</ref>\n| unpaid_circulation = 1,000,000+ (Online monthly)<ref name=\"circulation\" />\n| circulation_year = 2018\n| frequency = Quarterly\n| category = [[Politics]], [[culture]]\n| firstdate = Winter 2011\n| country = United States\n| based = New York\n| language = [[English language|English]]\n| website = [https://jacobinmag.com/ jacobinmag.com]\n| issn = 2158-2602\n}}\n'''''Jacobin''''' is a [[democratic socialist]] quarterly magazine based in [[New York City|New York]] offering [[American left|American leftist]] perspectives on politics, economics, and culture. Its paid print circulation is 40,000 and its website draws more than a million and a half views a month as of 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=About Us |url=https://jacobinmag.com/about |quote=The print magazine is released quarterly and reaches 40,000 subscribers, in addition to a web audience of 1,500,000 a month. |website=Jacobin |accessdate=15 August 2019}}</ref> [[Noam Chomsky]] has called the magazine \"a bright light in dark times\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Srinivasan|first1=Meera|title=The voice of the American Left|url=http://www.thehindu.com/opinion/op-ed/the-voice-of-the-american-left/article8433549.ece|work=[[The Hindu]]|date=5 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n== History and overview ==\nThe publication began as an online magazine released in September 2010,<ref>{{cite web|title=This is what you need to know|date=September 28, 2010|url=http://www.bookforum.com/blog/6491|publisher=[[Bookforum]]}}</ref> but it expanded into a print journal later that year.<ref>{{cite web|date=December 18, 2012|title=The Next Left: An Interview with Bhaskar Sunkara|first=Jake|last=Blumgart|url=http://new.bostonreview.net/BR37.6/jake_blumgart_bhaskar_sunkara_jacobin_magazine_marxism.php|work=[[Boston Review]]|access-date=October 28, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303221020/http://new.bostonreview.net/BR37.6/jake_blumgart_bhaskar_sunkara_jacobin_magazine_marxism.php|archive-date=March 3, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> ''Jacobin'' has been described by its founder [[Bhaskar Sunkara]] as a [[Radical Media|radical]] publication, \"largely the product of a younger generation not quite as tied to the Cold War paradigms that sustained the old leftist intellectual milieux like ''[[Dissent (American magazine)|Dissent]]'' or ''[[New Politics (magazine)|New Politics]]''\".<ref>{{cite web|title=No Short-Cuts: Interview with the Jacobin|url=http://idiommag.com/2011/03/no-short-cuts-interview-with-the-jacobin/|date=March 16, 2011|work=Idiom magazine}}</ref> Sunkara has said that the aim of the magazine was to create a publication which combined resolutely socialist politics with the accessibility of titles such as ''[[The Nation]]'' and ''[[The New Republic]]''.<ref name=nlr>{{cite journal |last1=Sunkara |first1=Bhaskar |author-link1=Bhaskar Sunkara |year=2014 |title=Interview: Project Jacobin|url=https://newleftreview.org/II/90/bhaskar-sunkara-project-jacobin |access-date=26 March 2018|journal=[[New Left Review]]|volume=90|pages=28-43}}</ref> He has also contrasted it to publications associated with small leftist groups, such as the [[International Socialist Organization]]'s ''[[Socialist Worker]]'' and ''International Socialist Review'' which were oriented towards party members and other revolutionary socialists, seeking a broader audience than those works whilst still anchoring the magazine in a [[Marxism|Marxist]] perspective.<ref name=revue /> In an interview he gave in 2018 Sunkara said that he intended for ''Jacobin'' to perform a similar role on the contemporary left to that undertaken by ''[[National Review]]'' on the post-war right, \"to cohere people around a set of ideas, and to interact with the mainstream of liberalism with that set of ideas\".<ref name=cjr />\n\nEarlier in 2013, Jacobin Books was announced, a partnership with [[Verso Books]] and [[Random House]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.versobooks.com/series_collections/112-jacobin |title=Jacobin Books series |author=Verso}}</ref> A collection of essays by ''Jacobin'' contributors was published by [[Henry Holt and Company]] in 2016. \"Class Action: An Activist Teacher's Handbook\", produced in conjunction with the [[Chicago Teachers Union]]'s CORE Caucus and Jacobin was distributed to trade union activists in the 16 cities in the United States and Canada.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://jacobinmag.com/2014/02/class-action-an-activist-teachers-handbook/ |title=Class Action: An Activist Teacher's Handbook |author=Bhaskar Sunkara |publisher=Jacobin}}</ref> Additionally, since the fall of 2014 it has sponsored more than 80 socialist reading groups.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://jacobinmag.com/reading-groups/ |title=Jacobin Reading Groups Listing |author=Jacobin}}</ref>\n\n''Jacobin'''s popularity grew with the increasing attention on socialist ideas stimulated by [[Bernie Sanders]]' [[Bernie Sanders 2016 presidential campaign|2016 presidential campaign]], with subscriptions tripling from 10,000 in the summer of 2015 to 32,000 as of the first issue of 2017, with 16,000 of the new subscribers being added in the two months after [[Donald Trump]]'s election.<ref name=cjr />\n\nIn 2017, ''Jacobin'' launched several podcasts, including ''The Dig'', hosted by journalist [[Daniel Denvir]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Jacobin Radio Is Here |url=https://jacobinmag.com/2017/01/jacobin-radio-podcast-daniel-denvir-dig-rl-stephens-suzi-weissman |website=Jacobin |accessdate=2 December 2019 |date=31 January 2017}}</ref>  In the spring of 2017, ''Jacobin'' editors collaborated with scholars [[Vivek Chibber]] and [[Robert Brenner]] to release the [[academic journal]] ''[[Catalyst (journal)|Catalyst: A Journal of Theory and Strategy]]''.<ref name=catalystjac>{{cite web|url=https://jacobinmag.com/2017/05/announcing-catalyst |title=Announcing Catalyst|author=<!--Not stated-->|date=May 4, 2017|website=[[Jacobin Magazine]]|publisher=[[Jacobin Magazine]]|accessdate=June 10, 2017|}}</ref> \n\nIn November 2018, the magazine's first foreign-language edition, ''Jacobin Italia'', was launched. Sunkara described it as \"a classic franchise model\", with the parent publication providing publishing and editorial advice and taking a small slice of revenue, but otherwise granting the Italian magazine autonomy.<ref name=cjr>{{cite web |url=https://www.cjr.org/special_report/the-abcs-of-jacobin-socialist-magazine.php/ |title=The ABCs of Jacobin |last=Baird |first=Robert P. |date=2 January 2019 |website=[[Columbia Journalism Review]]|access-date=4 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Title and logo ==\nThe name of the magazine derives from the book [[The Black Jacobins|''The Black Jacobins: Toussaint L'Ouverture and the San Domingo Revolution'']] by [[C. L. R. James]] in which James ascribes the Black [[Haitian Revolution|Haitian revolutionists]] a greater purity in regards to their attachment to the ideals of the [[French Revolution]] than the French [[Jacobin (politics)|Jacobins]].<ref name=revue>{{cite web|title=Jacobin Magazine: entretien avec Bhaskar Sunkara|url=http://revueperiode.net/jacobin-magazine-entretien-avec-bhaskar-sunkara/ |work=revueperiode.net (French) |date=October 19, 2015}}</ref> According to creative director Remeike Forbes, the logo was inspired by a scene in the movie ''[[Burn!]]'' referring to Nicaraguan national hero [[Jos\u00e9 Dolores Estrada]],<ref>{{cite web|title= The Black Jacobin. Our visual identity. |url=https://jacobinmag.com/2012/03/the-black-jacobin-2/ |date=Spring 2012 |first=Remeike|last=Forbes|work=Jacobin}}</ref> but it represents [[Toussaint Louverture]], the best-known leader of the most successful slave revolt in human history.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jacobin Magazine: entretien avec Bhaskar Sunkara|work=revueperiode.net (French)|url=http://revueperiode.net/jacobin-magazine-entretien-avec-bhaskar-sunkara/ |date=October 19, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe magazine's motto \"Reason in Revolt\" is a reference to a line from \"[[The Internationale]]\".\n\n== Contributors ==\nNotable ''Jacobin'' contributors have included [[Slavoj \u017di\u017eek]], [[Bob Herbert]], [[Yanis Varoufakis]], [[Hilary Wainwright]], [[Kareem Abdul-Jabbar]], [[Jeremy Corbyn]] and [[Pablo Iglesias Turri\u00f3n]]. Sunkara has said he feels that \"all of our writers fit within a broad socialist tradition\", noting that the magazine does sometimes publish articles by [[Modern liberalism in the United States|liberals]] and [[Social democracy|social democrats]], but that such pieces are written from a perspective that is consistent with the magazine's editorial vision, saying that \"we might publish a piece by a liberal advocating single-payer healthcare, because they\u2019re calling for the decommodification of a sector; and since we believe in the decommodification of the whole economy, it fits in\". In terms of the sociological background of contributors, Sunkara acknowledged that they were mostly under the age of 35 and stated that \"there are a lot of grad students, young adjunct professors or tenured professors. We also have quite a few organizers and union researchers involved [...] and people working in NGOs or around housing rights, that kind of thing\".<ref name=nlr />\n\n== Ideology ==\nIt has been variously described as [[Democratic socialism|democratic socialist]], socialist and Marxist.<ref name=\"Blumgart\"/><ref>{{cite news|last1=Matthews|first1=Dylan|title=Inside Jacobin: how a socialist magazine is winning the left's war of ideas|url=https://www.vox.com/2016/3/21/11265092/jacobin-bhaskar-sunkara|work=[[Vox (website)|Vox]]|date=21 March 2016}}</ref> According to an article published by the [[Nieman Foundation for Journalism|Nieman Journalism Lab]], it is a journal of \"democratic socialist thought\".<ref>{{cite news|last=O'Donovan|first=Caroline|title=Jacobin: A Marxist rag run on a lot of petty-bourgeois hustle|url=http://www.niemanlab.org/2014/09/jacobin-a-marxist-rag-run-on-a-lot-of-petty-bourgeois-hustle/|publisher=[[Nieman Foundation for Journalism|Nieman Journalism Lab]]|date=16 September 2014}}</ref> Writing in the ''[[New Statesman]]'', Max Strasser suggested that the journal claims to \"take the mantle of Marxist thought of [[Ralph Miliband]] and a similar vein of democratic socialism\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Strasser|first=Max|title=Who are the new socialist wunderkinds of America?|url=http://www.newstatesman.com/international-politics/2013/11/who-are-new-socialist-wunderkinds-america|work=[[New Statesman]]|date=9 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn an interview published in ''[[New Left Review]]'', Sunkara named a number of ideological influences on the magazine, including [[Michael Harrington]], who he described as \"very underrated as a popularizer of Marxist thought\"; Ralph Miliband and others influenced by [[Trotskyism]] without fully embracing it, such as [[Leo Panitch]]; theorists working in the [[Eurocommunist]] tradition; and \"Second International radicals\" including [[Vladimir Lenin]] and [[Karl Kautsky]].<ref name=nlr/>\n\nIn an article published in the ''[[Weekly Worker]]'', Jim Creegan highlighted the association of a number of the magazine's editors and writers with the [[Democratic Socialists of America]] (DSA), describing ''Jacobin'' as \"the closest thing to a flagship publication of the DSA left\" whilst also stressing the political diversity of contributors, incorporating \"everyone from social democratic liberals to avowed revolutionaries\". He also noted several features of the publication's editorial stance, namely its rejection of [[anti-communism]]; its skepticism regarding the possibility of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] being transformed into a social-democratic movement through internal pressure, advocating instead the formation of a mass-based independent labor party; criticism of the parties of the [[Socialist International]], which they argue have been responsible for imposing [[neoliberal]] [[austerity]] policies; and a conviction that the [[Nordic model]] of social democracy is ultimately not viable and that the only alternative to capitalism would be for militant labor and socialist movements to struggle to replace capitalism with socialism.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://weeklyworker.co.uk/worker/1195/walking-the-tightrope/ |title=Walking the Tightrope |last=Creegan |first=Jim |date=22 March 2018 |website=[[Weekly Worker]]|access-date=26 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n''[[The New York Times]]'' ran a profile of Sunkara in January 2013, commenting on the publication's unexpected success and engagement with mainstream liberalism.<ref>{{cite web|title=A Young Publisher Takes Marx Into the Mainstream|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/01/21/books/bhaskar-sunkara-editor-of-jacobin-magazine.html|date=January 1, 2013|first=Jennifer|last=Schuessler|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> In a 2013 article for ''[[Tablet (magazine)|Tablet]]'', [[Michelle Goldberg]] discussed ''Jacobin'' as part of a revival of interest in Marxism among young intellectuals.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tabletmag.com/jewish-news-and-politics/148162/young-intellectuals-find-marx=eschol |title=A Generation of Intellectuals Shaped by 2008 Crash Rescues Marx From History's Dustbin |work=Tablet |author=Michelle Goldberg}}</ref> Jake Blumgart, who contributed to the magazine in its early years, stated that it \"found an audience by mixing data-driven analysis and Marxist commentary with an irreverent and accessible style\".<ref name=\"Blumgart\">{{cite news|last1=Blumgart|first1=Jake|title=Jawnts: Giving socialism a good name|url=http://articles.philly.com/2016-02-08/news/70424478_1_socialism-fringe-publication|work=Philly.com|publisher=[[Philadelphia Media Network]]|date=6 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Podcasts ==\n*''The Dig'', hosted by journalist Daniel Denvir\n*''Jacobin Radio'', hosted by Suzi Weissman\n*''The Vast Majority'', hosted by ''Jacobin'' managing editor Micah Uetricht\n*''Behind the News'', hosted by journalist [[Doug Henwood]]<ref>{{cite web |title=A Warm Welcome to Behind the News |url=https://jacobinmag.com/2017/03/behind-news-doug-henwood-jacobin-radio-podcast |website=Jacobin |accessdate=2 December 2019 |date=22 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n\n{{refbegin}}\n\n* {{Cite web| last = Arrieta-Kenna| first = Ruair\u00ed| title = How the Cool Kids of the Left Turned on Elizabeth Warren| work = [[Politico]]| accessdate = 2019-12-10| date = 2019-12-08| url = https://www.politico.com/news/magazine/2019/12/08/elizabeth-warren-jacobin-socialist-left-072693}}\n\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{official website|https://jacobinmag.com/}}\n\n[[Category:Socialist magazines|Jacobin]]\n[[Category:American quarterly magazines|Jacobin]]\n[[Category:Magazines established in 2010|Jacobin]]\n[[Category:Socialism in the United States|Jacobin]]\n[[Category:2010 establishments in New York City]]\n[[Category:American political magazines]]\n[[Category:Magazines published in New York City]]\n[[Category:Marxist magazines]]\n[[Category:Socialist newspapers published in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{redirect|Catalyst (journal)|the Australian publication|Catalyst (magazine)}}\n{{Infobox magazine\n| title = Jacobin\n| image_file = File:Jacobin fall 2013 cover.jpg\n| image_size = 225px\n| image_caption = Issue 11/12 (fall 2013)\n| editor = [[Bhaskar Sunkara]]\n| editor_title = Publisher\n| paid_circulation = 40,000<ref name=\"circulation\">{{cite news |last1=Baird |first1=Robert |title=The ABCs of Jacobin |url=https://www.cjr.org/special_report/the-abcs-of-jacobin-socialist-magazine.php |accessdate=8 September 2019 |work=Columbia Journalism Review |language=en}}</ref>\n| unpaid_circulation = 1,000,000+ (Online monthly)<ref name=\"circulation\" />\n| circulation_year = 2018\n| frequency = Quarterly\n| category = [[Politics]], [[culture]]\n| firstdate = Winter 2011\n| country = United States\n| based = New York\n| language = [[English language|English]]\n| website = [https://jacobinmag.com/ jacobinmag.com]\n| issn = 2158-2602\n}}\n'''''Jacobin''''' is a [[democratic socialist]] quarterly magazine based in [[New York City|New York]] offering [[American left|American leftist]] perspectives on politics, economics, and culture. Its paid print circulation is 40,000 and its website draws more than a million and a half views a month as of 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=About Us |url=https://jacobinmag.com/about |quote=The print magazine is released quarterly and reaches 40,000 subscribers, in addition to a web audience of 1,500,000 a month. |website=Jacobin |accessdate=15 August 2019}}</ref> [[Noam Chomsky]] has called the magazine \"a bright light in dark times\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Srinivasan|first1=Meera|title=The voice of the American Left|url=http://www.thehindu.com/opinion/op-ed/the-voice-of-the-american-left/article8433549.ece|work=[[The Hindu]]|date=5 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n== History and overview ==\nThe publication began as an online magazine released in September 2010,<ref>{{cite web|title=This is what you need to know|date=September 28, 2010|url=http://www.bookforum.com/blog/6491|publisher=[[Bookforum]]}}</ref> but it expanded into a print journal later that year.<ref>{{cite web|date=December 18, 2012|title=The Next Left: An Interview with Bhaskar Sunkara|first=Jake|last=Blumgart|url=http://new.bostonreview.net/BR37.6/jake_blumgart_bhaskar_sunkara_jacobin_magazine_marxism.php|work=[[Boston Review]]|access-date=October 28, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303221020/http://new.bostonreview.net/BR37.6/jake_blumgart_bhaskar_sunkara_jacobin_magazine_marxism.php|archive-date=March 3, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> ''Jacobin'' has been described by its founder [[Bhaskar Sunkara]] as a [[Radical Media|radical]] publication, \"largely the product of a younger generation not quite as tied to the Cold War paradigms that sustained the old leftist intellectual milieux like ''[[Dissent (American magazine)|Dissent]]'' or ''[[New Politics (magazine)|New Politics]]''\".<ref>{{cite web|title=No Short-Cuts: Interview with the Jacobin|url=http://idiommag.com/2011/03/no-short-cuts-interview-with-the-jacobin/|date=March 16, 2011|work=Idiom magazine}}</ref> Sunkara has said that the aim of the magazine was to create a publication which combined resolutely socialist politics with the accessibility of titles such as ''[[The Nation]]'' and ''[[The New Republic]]''.<ref name=nlr>{{cite journal |last1=Sunkara |first1=Bhaskar |author-link1=Bhaskar Sunkara |year=2014 |title=Interview: Project Jacobin|url=https://newleftreview.org/II/90/bhaskar-sunkara-project-jacobin |access-date=26 March 2018|journal=[[New Left Review]]|volume=90|pages=28-43}}</ref> He has also contrasted it to publications associated with small leftist groups, such as the [[International Socialist Organization]]'s ''[[Socialist Worker]]'' and ''International Socialist Review'' which were oriented towards party members and other revolutionary socialists, seeking a broader audience than those works whilst still anchoring the magazine in a [[Marxism|Marxist]] perspective.<ref name=revue /> In an interview he gave in 2018 Sunkara said that he intended for ''Jacobin'' to perform a similar role on the contemporary left to that undertaken by ''[[National Review]]'' on the post-war right, \"to cohere people around a set of ideas, and to interact with the mainstream of liberalism with that set of ideas\".<ref name=cjr />\n\nEarlier in 2013, Jacobin Books was announced, a partnership with [[Verso Books]] and [[Random House]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.versobooks.com/series_collections/112-jacobin |title=Jacobin Books series |author=Verso}}</ref> A collection of essays by ''Jacobin'' contributors was published by [[Henry Holt and Company]] in 2016. \"Class Action: An Activist Teacher's Handbook\", produced in conjunction with the [[Chicago Teachers Union]]'s CORE Caucus and Jacobin was distributed to trade union activists in the 16 cities in the United States and Canada.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://jacobinmag.com/2014/02/class-action-an-activist-teachers-handbook/ |title=Class Action: An Activist Teacher's Handbook |author=Bhaskar Sunkara |publisher=Jacobin}}</ref> Additionally, since the fall of 2014 it has sponsored more than 80 socialist reading groups.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://jacobinmag.com/reading-groups/ |title=Jacobin Reading Groups Listing |author=Jacobin}}</ref>\n\n''Jacobin'''s popularity grew with the increasing attention on socialist ideas stimulated by [[Bernie Sanders]]' [[Bernie Sanders 2016 presidential campaign|2016 presidential campaign]], with subscriptions tripling from 10,000 in the summer of 2015 to 32,000 as of the first issue of 2017, with 16,000 of the new subscribers being added in the two months after [[Donald Trump]]'s election.<ref name=cjr />\n\nIn 2017, ''Jacobin'' launched several podcasts, including ''The Dig'', hosted by journalist [[Daniel Denvir]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Jacobin Radio Is Here |url=https://jacobinmag.com/2017/01/jacobin-radio-podcast-daniel-denvir-dig-rl-stephens-suzi-weissman |website=Jacobin |accessdate=2 December 2019 |date=31 January 2017}}</ref>  In the spring of 2017, ''Jacobin'' editors collaborated with scholars [[Vivek Chibber]] and [[Robert Brenner]] to release the [[academic journal]] ''[[Catalyst (journal)|Catalyst: A Journal of Theory and Strategy]]''.<ref name=catalystjac>{{cite web|url=https://jacobinmag.com/2017/05/announcing-catalyst |title=Announcing Catalyst|author=<!--Not stated-->|date=May 4, 2017|website=[[Jacobin Magazine]]|publisher=[[Jacobin Magazine]]|accessdate=June 10, 2017|}}</ref> \n\nIn November 2018 the magazine's first foreign-language edition, ''Jacobin Italia'', was launched: Sunkara described it as \"a classic franchise model\", with the parent publication providing publishing and editorial advice and taking a small slice of revenue, but otherwise granting the Italian magazine autonomy.<ref name=cjr>{{cite web |url=https://www.cjr.org/special_report/the-abcs-of-jacobin-socialist-magazine.php/ |title=The ABCs of Jacobin |last=Baird |first=Robert P. |date=2 January 2019 |website=[[Columbia Journalism Review]]|access-date=4 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Title and logo ==\nThe name of the magazine derives from the book [[The Black Jacobins|''The Black Jacobins: Toussaint L'Ouverture and the San Domingo Revolution'']] by [[C. L. R. James]] in which James ascribes the Black [[Haitian Revolution|Haitian revolutionists]] a greater purity in regards to their attachment to the ideals of the [[French Revolution]] than the French [[Jacobin (politics)|Jacobins]].<ref name=revue>{{cite web|title=Jacobin Magazine: entretien avec Bhaskar Sunkara|url=http://revueperiode.net/jacobin-magazine-entretien-avec-bhaskar-sunkara/ |work=revueperiode.net (French) |date=October 19, 2015}}</ref> According to creative director Remeike Forbes, the logo was inspired by a scene in the movie ''[[Burn!]]'' referring to Nicaraguan national hero [[Jos\u00e9 Dolores Estrada]],<ref>{{cite web|title= The Black Jacobin. Our visual identity. |url=https://jacobinmag.com/2012/03/the-black-jacobin-2/ |date=Spring 2012 |first=Remeike|last=Forbes|work=Jacobin}}</ref> but it represents [[Toussaint Louverture]], the best-known leader of the most successful slave revolt in human history.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jacobin Magazine: entretien avec Bhaskar Sunkara|work=revueperiode.net (French)|url=http://revueperiode.net/jacobin-magazine-entretien-avec-bhaskar-sunkara/ |date=October 19, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe magazine's motto \"Reason in Revolt\" is a reference to a line from \"[[The Internationale]]\".\n\n== Contributors ==\nNotable ''Jacobin'' contributors have included [[Slavoj \u017di\u017eek]], [[Bob Herbert]], [[Yanis Varoufakis]], [[Hilary Wainwright]], [[Kareem Abdul-Jabbar]], [[Jeremy Corbyn]] and [[Pablo Iglesias Turri\u00f3n]]. Sunkara has said he feels that \"all of our writers fit within a broad socialist tradition\", noting that the magazine does sometimes publish articles by [[Modern liberalism in the United States|liberals]] and [[Social democracy|social democrats]], but that such pieces are written from a perspective that is consistent with the magazine's editorial vision, saying that \"we might publish a piece by a liberal advocating single-payer healthcare, because they\u2019re calling for the decommodification of a sector; and since we believe in the decommodification of the whole economy, it fits in\". In terms of the sociological background of contributors, Sunkara acknowledged that they were mostly under the age of 35 and stated that \"there are a lot of grad students, young adjunct professors or tenured professors. We also have quite a few organizers and union researchers involved [...] and people working in NGOs or around housing rights, that kind of thing\".<ref name=nlr />\n\n== Ideology ==\nIt has been variously described as [[Democratic socialism|democratic socialist]], socialist and Marxist.<ref name=\"Blumgart\"/><ref>{{cite news|last1=Matthews|first1=Dylan|title=Inside Jacobin: how a socialist magazine is winning the left's war of ideas|url=https://www.vox.com/2016/3/21/11265092/jacobin-bhaskar-sunkara|work=[[Vox (website)|Vox]]|date=21 March 2016}}</ref> According to an article published by the [[Nieman Foundation for Journalism|Nieman Journalism Lab]], it is a journal of \"democratic socialist thought\".<ref>{{cite news|last=O'Donovan|first=Caroline|title=Jacobin: A Marxist rag run on a lot of petty-bourgeois hustle|url=http://www.niemanlab.org/2014/09/jacobin-a-marxist-rag-run-on-a-lot-of-petty-bourgeois-hustle/|publisher=[[Nieman Foundation for Journalism|Nieman Journalism Lab]]|date=16 September 2014}}</ref> Writing in the ''[[New Statesman]]'', Max Strasser suggested that the journal claims to \"take the mantle of Marxist thought of [[Ralph Miliband]] and a similar vein of democratic socialism\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Strasser|first=Max|title=Who are the new socialist wunderkinds of America?|url=http://www.newstatesman.com/international-politics/2013/11/who-are-new-socialist-wunderkinds-america|work=[[New Statesman]]|date=9 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn an interview published in ''[[New Left Review]]'', Sunkara named a number of ideological influences on the magazine, including [[Michael Harrington]], who he described as \"very underrated as a popularizer of Marxist thought\"; Ralph Miliband and others influenced by [[Trotskyism]] without fully embracing it, such as [[Leo Panitch]]; theorists working in the [[Eurocommunist]] tradition; and \"Second International radicals\" including [[Vladimir Lenin]] and [[Karl Kautsky]].<ref name=nlr/>\n\nIn an article published in the ''[[Weekly Worker]]'', Jim Creegan highlighted the association of a number of the magazine's editors and writers with the [[Democratic Socialists of America]] (DSA), describing ''Jacobin'' as \"the closest thing to a flagship publication of the DSA left\" whilst also stressing the political diversity of contributors, incorporating \"everyone from social democratic liberals to avowed revolutionaries\". He also noted several features of the publication's editorial stance, namely its rejection of [[anti-communism]]; its skepticism regarding the possibility of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] being transformed into a social-democratic movement through internal pressure, advocating instead the formation of a mass-based independent labor party; criticism of the parties of the [[Socialist International]], which they argue have been responsible for imposing [[neoliberal]] [[austerity]] policies; and a conviction that the [[Nordic model]] of social democracy is ultimately not viable and that the only alternative to capitalism would be for militant labor and socialist movements to struggle to replace capitalism with socialism.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://weeklyworker.co.uk/worker/1195/walking-the-tightrope/ |title=Walking the Tightrope |last=Creegan |first=Jim |date=22 March 2018 |website=[[Weekly Worker]]|access-date=26 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n''[[The New York Times]]'' ran a profile of Sunkara in January 2013, commenting on the publication's unexpected success and engagement with mainstream liberalism.<ref>{{cite web|title=A Young Publisher Takes Marx Into the Mainstream|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/01/21/books/bhaskar-sunkara-editor-of-jacobin-magazine.html|date=January 1, 2013|first=Jennifer|last=Schuessler|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> In a 2013 article for ''[[Tablet (magazine)|Tablet]]'', [[Michelle Goldberg]] discussed ''Jacobin'' as part of a revival of interest in Marxism among young intellectuals.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tabletmag.com/jewish-news-and-politics/148162/young-intellectuals-find-marx=eschol |title=A Generation of Intellectuals Shaped by 2008 Crash Rescues Marx From History's Dustbin |work=Tablet |author=Michelle Goldberg}}</ref> Jake Blumgart, who contributed to the magazine in its early years, stated that it \"found an audience by mixing data-driven analysis and Marxist commentary with an irreverent and accessible style\".<ref name=\"Blumgart\">{{cite news|last1=Blumgart|first1=Jake|title=Jawnts: Giving socialism a good name|url=http://articles.philly.com/2016-02-08/news/70424478_1_socialism-fringe-publication|work=Philly.com|publisher=[[Philadelphia Media Network]]|date=6 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Podcasts ==\n*''The Dig'', hosted by journalist Daniel Denvir\n*''Jacobin Radio'', hosted by Suzi Weissman\n*''The Vast Majority'', hosted by ''Jacobin'' managing editor Micah Uetricht\n*''Behind the News'', hosted by journalist [[Doug Henwood]]<ref>{{cite web |title=A Warm Welcome to Behind the News |url=https://jacobinmag.com/2017/03/behind-news-doug-henwood-jacobin-radio-podcast |website=Jacobin |accessdate=2 December 2019 |date=22 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n\n{{refbegin}}\n\n* {{Cite web| last = Arrieta-Kenna| first = Ruair\u00ed| title = How the Cool Kids of the Left Turned on Elizabeth Warren| work = [[Politico]]| accessdate = 2019-12-10| date = 2019-12-08| url = https://www.politico.com/news/magazine/2019/12/08/elizabeth-warren-jacobin-socialist-left-072693}}\n\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{official website|https://jacobinmag.com/}}\n\n[[Category:Socialist magazines|Jacobin]]\n[[Category:American quarterly magazines|Jacobin]]\n[[Category:Magazines established in 2010|Jacobin]]\n[[Category:Socialism in the United States|Jacobin]]\n[[Category:2010 establishments in New York City]]\n[[Category:American political magazines]]\n[[Category:Magazines published in New York City]]\n[[Category:Marxist magazines]]\n[[Category:Socialist newspapers published in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Davide King", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory and overview:was launched\u02d0 ---> was launched.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jacobin_(magazine)"}
{"title_page": "Education in Greece", "text_new": "{{Copy edit|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox Education\n|country name = Greece\n|agency image = [[File:Coat of arms of Greece.svg|100px]] \n|agency = [[Ministry of Education and Religious Affairs]]\n|leader titles = [[Minister for National Education and Religious Affairs (Greece)|Minister]] |\n|leader names = Niki Kerameus\n|budget = 12,08 billion [[Euro|\u20ac]] (public)<br>\n4% of [[Gross Domestic Product|GDP]]<ref name=\"Policy, Politics, and Social Inequality in the Educational System of Greece\"/><ref name=\"Government expenditure on education, total (% of GDP) - Greece\">{{cite journal|url=https://data.worldbank.org/indicator/SE.XPD.TOTL.GD.ZS?locations=GR&most_recent_value_desc=true |title=Government expenditure on education, total (% of GDP) - Greece |publisher=The World Bank}} UNESCO Institute for Statistics {{in lang|en}}</ref>       \n|budget year = 2010\n|primary languages = [[Greek language|Greek]]\n|system type = National\n|established events = \n|established dates = \n|literacy year = 2014\n|literacy total = 98%\n|literacy men = 99%\n|literacy women = 97%\n|enroll total = 1,426,175\n|enroll primary = 786,025<sup>1<sup>  \n|enroll secondary = 360,248<sup>2<sup>  \n|enroll post-secondary = 276,902<sup>3<sup>  \n|attain secondary = \n|attain post-secondary =\n|footnotes =<sup>1</sup> 2000-2001 school year<ref name=\"Policy, Politics, and Social Inequality in the Educational System of Greece\">{{cite journal |doi= 10.1353/mgs.2006.0004 |title=Policy, Politics, and Social Inequality in the Educational System of Greece |journal=Journal of Modern Greek Studies |publisher=Johns Hopkins University Press. Official publication of the Modern Greek Studies Association (MGSA). |volume=24 |issue=7 |pages=1\u201321 |date=May 2006 |last1=Giamouridis |first1 = A.|last2= Bagley |first2=C. |url= |ISSN= 1086-3265}}{{in lang|en}} \n* For the Gross Domestic Product (GDP), see page 6\n* For the 2000-2001 school year, see page 24 table 6.2</ref><br/><sup>2</sup> 2000-2001; loc. cit.<br/><sup>3</sup> 1999-2000\n}}\n<!---Please do not change data and ages for different grades without first discussing on the talk page. Please furnish a reliable citation for the change. Otherwise, expect changes to be reverted---->\n\n'''Education in Greece''' at all levels is centralized by the [[Ministry of Education and Religious Affairs]] (\u03a5.\u03a0\u0391\u0399.\u0398.). The Ministry exercises control over public schools, formulates and implements legislation, administers the budget, administers and coordinates national level university entrance examinations, sets up the [[national curriculum]], appoints public school teaching staff, and coordinates other services. The national supervisory role of the Ministry is exercised through [[regional units of Greece|Regional Unit]] Public Education Offices which are named Regional Directorates of Primary and Secondary School Education.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eacea.ec.europa.eu/national-policies/eurydice/content/administration-and-governance-central-andor-regional-level-33_en |title=Greece Administration and Governance at Central and/or Regional Level |publisher=European Commission}}{{in lang|en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://eacea.ec.europa.eu/national-policies/eurydice/content/legislation-27_en |title=Greece Education System Legislation and Official Policy Documents|publisher=European Commission}}{{in lang|en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://eacea.ec.europa.eu/national-policies/eurydice/content/institutions-11_en |title=Bodies and Institutions Supervised by Greek Ministry of Education |publisher=European Commission}}{{in lang|en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.european-agency.org/country-information/greece/legislation-and-policy |title=Greece inclusion of learners with special educational needs and/or disabilities |publisher=European Agency for Special Needs and Inclusive Education}} Information for Greece - Legislation and policy {{in lang|en}}</ref><ref name=\"Authority for Quality Assurance in Primary and Secondary Education (ADIPPDE)\">{{cite journal|url=http://www.adippde.gr/ |title=Authority for Quality Assurance in Primary and Secondary Education (ADIPPDE) |publisher=Ministry of Education}}{{in lang|el}}</ref> \nPublic schools and textbooks are funded by the government. About 25% of postgraduate programmes offer free tuition, while about 30% of students are eligible to attend programmes tuition-free based on individual criteria.<ref name=\"Law 4485/2017 Government Gazette 114 \u0391'/04.08.2017\"/> [[Formal education]] in [[Greece]] comprises three [[educational stage]]s. The first stage of formal education is the Primary stage (\u0394\u03b7\u03bc\u03bf\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc, six years, ages 6 to 12), followed by the Secondary stage which separates into two sub-stages: the compulsory [[Gymnasium (school)|Gymnasio]] (\u0393\u03c5\u03bc\u03bd\u03ac\u03c3\u03b9\u03bf, three years, ages 12 to 15) and non-compulsory [[Lyceum]] (\u039b\u03cd\u03ba\u03b5\u03b9\u03bf, three years, ages 15 to 18).<ref name=\"Greece Geodata Government Maps\">{{cite journal|url=http://geodata.gov.gr/maps/?locale=en/ |title=Greece Geodata Government Maps |publisher=Information Management Systems Institute (IMSI) / Research and Innovation Center \"Athena\"}} {{in lang|en|el}}</ref> The third stage involves higher education. School holidays in Greece include Christmas, [[Greek Independence Day]], Easter, [[Ohi Day|National Anniversary Day]], a three-month summer holiday, [[Public holidays in Greece|National Public Holidays]], and local holidays which vary by region such as the local Saint's Day. In addition to schooling, the majority of students attend extracurricular private classes at private centres called \"frontistiria\" (''\u03c6\u03c1\u03bf\u03bd\u03c4\u03b9\u03c3\u03c4\u03ae\u03c1\u03b9\u03b1'', ''[[frontistirio]]'') or one-to-one tuition, which prepare students for higher education admission, like the Pan-Hellenic Examinations, and to learn foreign languages. \nStudents on the school premises possess mobile phones or other electronic devices, like the [[smartwatch]]es, in-ear headphones, are prohibited by law.<ref name=\"Law 2472/1997 Government Gazette 50 A\u2019/10.04.1997\">{{cite journal|url= https://www.dpa.gr/pls/portal/docs/PAGE/APDPX/ENGLISH_INDEX/LEGAL%20FRAMEWORK/LAW%202472-97-NOV2013-EN.PDF |title=Law 2472/1997 Government Gazette 50 A\u2019/10.04.1997 |publisher=Hellenic Data Protection Authority (HDPA)}} Protection of Individuals with regard to the Processing of Personal Data {{in lang|en}}</ref><ref name=\"Law 3471/2006 Government Gazette 133 A\u2019/28.06.2006\">{{cite journal|url=http://www.adae.gr/fileadmin/docs/nomoi/LAW_3471-2006-EN.pdf |title=Law 3471/2006 Government Gazette 133 A\u2019/28.06.2006 |publisher=Hellenic Authority for Communication Security and Privacy (ADAE)}} Protection of personal data and privacy in the electronic telecommunications sector and amendment of law 2472/1997 {{in lang|en}}</ref><ref name=\"Greece cyber security laws and regulations\">{{cite news|url=https://iclg.com/practice-areas/cybersecurity-laws-and-regulations/greece |title=Greece cyber security laws and regulations|publisher=Global Legal Group (ICLG) UK, The International Corporate Legal Guides and International Business Reports |last1=Giannakakis |first1=Ioannis  |last2=Vitoratos |first2=Stefanos  |date=October 10, 2019|access-date=January 1, 2020|newspaper=}} Contributing firm: G+P Law Firm Athens, Greece, www.gplawfirm.eu {{in lang|en}}</ref><ref name=\"Cyber security laws and regulations of country jurisdiction chapters 2020\">{{cite news|url=https://iclg.com/practice-areas/cybersecurity-laws-and-regulations#countrychapters  |title=Cyber security laws and regulations of country jurisdiction chapters 2020 |publisher=Global Legal Group (ICLG) UK |access-date=February 1, 2020}} {{in lang|en}}</ref>\n \n__TOC__\n\n==Diagram==\n<!---Please do not change ages for different grades. Otherwise, expect changes to be reverted---->\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"   \n! colspan=\"5\" | Greece Framework \n|-\n! colspan=\"5\" | Compulsory School Education PK9 \n|-\n|- \n! colspan=\"2\" | Year in Schooling\n! Age\n! Designation  \n! Educational Stage\n|-   \n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Pre-kindergarten]]  \n| Year 1\n| 4\u20135\n| Pre-kindergarten\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[Preschool]]\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Kindergarten]] \n| Year 2\n| 5\u20136\n| Kindergarten\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[First grade]]  \n| Year 1 \n| 6\u20137\n| 1st Grade\n| rowspan=6 | [[Primary school|Primary School]]\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Second grade]]  \n| Year 2\n| 7\u20138\n| 2nd Grade\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Third grade]]   \n| Year 3\n| 8\u20139\n| 3rd Grade\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Fourth grade]]  \n| Year 4\n| 9\u201310\n| 4th Grade\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Fifth grade]]  \n| Year 5\n| 10\u201311\n| 5th Grade \n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Sixth grade]]   \n| Year 6\n| 11\u201312\n| 6th Grade\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Seventh grade]]  \n| Year 7\n| 12\u201313\n| 1st Grade\n| rowspan=3 | [[Secondary school|Lower Secondary School]]<br>(It is called [[Gymnasium (school)|Gymnasium]])\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Eighth grade]]   \n| Year 8\n| 13\u201314\n| 2nd Grade\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Ninth grade]]   \n| Year 9\n| 14\u201315\n| 3rd Grade\n|-\n|-\n! colspan=\"5\" | Non-Compulsory School Education\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Tenth grade]]   \n| Year 10\n| 15\u201316\n| 1st Grade\n| rowspan=3 | [[Secondary school|Upper Secondary School]]<br>(It is called [[Lyceum#Greece|Lyceum]])<br>(US equivalent: High School) \n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Eleventh grade]]  \n| Year 11\n| 16\u201317\n| 2nd Grade\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Twelfth grade]]  \n| Year 12\n| 17\u201318\n| 3rd Grade\n|}\n\n==Preschool==\n<!---Please do not change content and ages for different grades. Otherwise, expect changes to be reverted----> \nMost [[preschool]]s, also known as pre-primary, are attached to and share buildings with a [[primary school]]. Preschool is [[Compulsory education|compulsory]] and lasts 2 years, split into 1 year of [[Pre-kindergarten]] (''\u03a0\u03c1\u03bf\u03bd\u03b7\u03c0\u03b9\u03b1\u03b3\u03c9\u03b3\u03b5\u03af\u03bf'') and 1 year of [[Kindergarten]] (''\u039d\u03b7\u03c0\u03b9\u03b1\u03b3\u03c9\u03b3\u03b5\u03af\u03bf''; ''Nipiagogeio'').<ref name=\"Paragraph 3, Article 33, Law 4521/02.03.2018, Government Gazette 38 A\u2019\">{{cite journal|url=https://www.hellenicparliament.gr/UserFiles/bcc26661-143b-4f2d-8916-0e0e66ba4c50/i-uniwest-pap-olo.pdf#page=33 |title=Paragraph 3, Article 33, Law 4521/02.03.2018, Government Gazette 38 A\u2019 |publisher=Hellenic Parliament}}{{in lang|el}}</ref> Since the school year 2018\u20132019, children who would be four years of age by December 31 are required to begin attending preschool on September 11 of the same year.{{efn|If September 11 is a Saturday or Sunday, then the start date would be the following Monday.}} Applications for registration and enrollment are usually carried out annually, during fifteen consecutive days in May. After this period expires, students are allowed neither to register nor to enroll.\n* 1st Year / Pre-Kindergarten (''\u03a0\u03c1\u03bf\u03bd\u03b7\u03c0\u03b9\u03b1\u03b3\u03c9\u03b3\u03b5\u03af\u03bf''), age 4 to 5 years old (with some 3 year olds, about to turn 4, attending){{ref|d|[C]}} \n* 2nd Year / Kindergarten (''\u039d\u03b7\u03c0\u03b9\u03b1\u03b3\u03c9\u03b3\u03b5\u03af\u03bf''), age 5 to 6 (with some 4 year olds, about to turn 5, attending)\n\n{{notelist}}\n\n==Primary education==\n<!---Please do not change content and ages for different grades. Otherwise, expect changes to be reverted---->\n\n[[Primary school]] (\u0394\u03b7\u03bc\u03bf\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc, ''Dimotiko'') compulsory education 6 years.<ref name=\"School E-Books of Primary, Gymnasium, General Lyceum, EPAL Lyceum\">{{cite journal|url=http://ebooks.edu.gr/new/allcourses.php|title=School E-Books of Primary, Gymnasium, General Lyceum, EPAL Lyceum|publisher=[[:el: \u0399\u03bd\u03c3\u03c4\u03b9\u03c4\u03bf\u03cd\u03c4\u03bf \u03a4\u03b5\u03c7\u03bd\u03bf\u03bb\u03bf\u03b3\u03af\u03b1\u03c2 \u03a5\u03c0\u03bf\u03bb\u03bf\u03b3\u03b9\u03c3\u03c4\u03ce\u03bd \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u0395\u03ba\u03b4\u03cc\u03c3\u03b5\u03c9\u03bd|\u0399\u03a4\u03a5\u0395 \u0394\u03b9\u03cc\u03c6\u03b1\u03bd\u03c4\u03bf\u03c2]] Computer Technology Institute and Press (CTI) Diophantus}}{{in lang|el}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.minedu.gov.gr/publications/docs2018/25_02_19sch_odigos.pdf|title=School Guide for Primary and Preschool Education|date=11 February 2019|publisher=Computer Technology Institute and Press (CTI) Diophantus}}{{in lang|el}}</ref>\n\nIn Year 1 and Year 2, pupils are not officially graded. Grading begins in Year 3, and written exams are introduced in Year 5.\nAutomatic progression exists from the one year to the next year. School year starts on September 11 and ends on June 15. School day starts at 08.15 hour and finishes at 13.15 hour. It comprises six academic years of schooling name \u03c4\u03ac\u03be\u03b5\u03b9\u03c2 (grades), numbered 1 through to 6. Enrollment to the next tier of compulsory education, the Gymnasium, is automatic. The classes a week for a subject vary from the teacher who teaches. It is awarded \"\u0391\u03c0\u03bf\u03bb\u03c5\u03c4\u03ae\u03c1\u03b9\u03bf \u0394\u03b7\u03bc\u03bf\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03bf\u03cd\" (''Apolytirio Dimotikou'', primary school leaving certificate) which gives automatic admission to the lower secondary education (gymnasium). \u0391ges are typical and can vary with the most common ages approximately:{{ref|d|[C]}}  \n{{col-begin|width=90%}} \n{{col-2}}\n; Grades of Primary School\nGrade 1\u20136 \n* 1st Year / First grade (''\u03a0\u03c1\u03ce\u03c4\u03b7 \u03c4\u03ac\u03be\u03b7 \u03b4\u03b7\u03bc\u03bf\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03bf\u03cd''), age 6 to 7-year-olds\n* 2nd Year / Second grade (''\u0394\u03b5\u03c5\u03c4\u03ad\u03c1\u03b1 \u03c4\u03ac\u03be\u03b7 \u03b4\u03b7\u03bc\u03bf\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03bf\u03cd''), age 7 to 8\n* 3rd Year / Third grade (''\u03a4\u03c1\u03af\u03c4\u03b7 \u03c4\u03ac\u03be\u03b7 \u03b4\u03b7\u03bc\u03bf\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03bf\u03cd''), age 8 to 9\n* 4th Year / Fourth grade (''\u03a4\u03b5\u03c4\u03ac\u03c1\u03c4\u03b7 \u03c4\u03ac\u03be\u03b7 \u03b4\u03b7\u03bc\u03bf\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03bf\u03cd''), age 9 to 10\n* 5th Year / Fifth grade (''\u03a0\u03ad\u03bc\u03c0\u03c4\u03b7 \u03c4\u03ac\u03be\u03b7 \u03b4\u03b7\u03bc\u03bf\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03bf\u03cd''), age 10 to 11\n* 6th Year / Sixth grade (''\u0388\u03ba\u03c4\u03b7 \u03c4\u03ac\u03be\u03b7 \u03b4\u03b7\u03bc\u03bf\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03bf\u03cd''), age 11 to 12\n{{col-2}}\n; Grading System  \n{{main|Academic grading in Greece}}\n* 1st Year: no grade points\n* 2nd Year: no grade points \n* 3rd Year: A\u2013D \n* 4th Year: A\u2013D\n* 5th Year: 1\u201310\n* 6th Year: 1\u201310 \n{{col-end}}\n\n'''Primary School Curriculum'''\n{| border=\"0\" \n|-\n| '''Subjects of Primary School'''\n| colspan=\"6\"| '''Weekly Hours of Grades'''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\" \n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| (school year 2019-2020)\n||1st  \n||2nd  \n||3rd  \n||4th\n||5th\n||6th\n|-\n| Modern Greek Language\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|9\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|9\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|8\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|8\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|7\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|7\n|-\n| Mathematics \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|5\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|5\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|4\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|4\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|4\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|4\n|-\n| Art\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n| Music \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n| History                                                     \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n|-\n| Physics              \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\n|-\n| Geography                                     \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n|-\n| Flexible Zone                               \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|-\n|-\n| Religious Studies                     \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n| Computer Studies                     \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n| Physical Education      \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n|-\n| Theatrical Education                                   \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|-\n|-\n| Environmental Studies      \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|4\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|4\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|-\n|-\n| Social and Political Studies            \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n| English Language (Modern)                  \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\n|-\n| 2nd Foreign Language (Modern; French or German)\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n|-\n| '''Primary School Total Weekly Hours of Grades:'''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|30\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|30 \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|30 \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|30 \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|30 \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|30 \n|-\n|}\n\n==Secondary education==\n[[File:1\u03bf \u0393\u03c5\u03bc\u03bd\u03ac\u03c3\u03b9\u03bf \u0399\u03c9\u03b1\u03bd\u03bd\u03af\u03bd\u03c9\u03bd 3.jpg|thumb|[[Zosimaia School]], [[Ioannina]]]]\n[[File:Saloniki Jewish school entrance.jpg|thumb|View of the Jewish school, [[Thessaloniki]]]]\n[[File:Astros public school.jpg|thumb|The public school of [[Astros, Greece|Astros]], built in 1915.]]\n\n===Gymnasium===\n[[Gymnasium (school)|Gymnasium]] (\u0393\u03c5\u03bc\u03bd\u03ac\u03c3\u03b9\u03bf, ''Gimnasio'', Lower Secondary Education School) compulsory education 3 years.\n\nArticle 16, Paragraph 3 of the Constitution of 1975 laid down that compulsory education should be nine years in length. \nThis constitutional provision, to apply to all Greek children, was enshrined in Law 309/1976, by which also was replaced classical Greek ([[Greek diacritics|polytonic system]], [[katharevousa]]) by modern Greek (monotonic system, single-accent, [[Demotic Greek|dimotiki]]), as the official language for teaching at all levels of education, and ceased to be a one-tier non-compulsory six years lower and upper secondary school named gymnasium (pupils aged 12\u201318), converted to compulsory three years lower secondary school for pupils aged 12\u201315 named gymnasium and three years non-compulsory upper secondary school for pupils aged 15\u201318 named lyceum.\n\nAdmitted students can have a maximum age up to 16-year-old, while must have Primary Education School Certificate or its international equivalent. No entry exams required. Schooling starts on September 11 and ends on early June before the first day of the Pan-Hellenic Examinations. The lessons end on 31 May so that the students will be able to study for their examinations in early June. The gumnasium school awarded qualification \"\u0391\u03c0\u03bf\u03bb\u03c5\u03c4\u03ae\u03c1\u03b9\u03bf \u0393\u03c5\u03bc\u03bd\u03b1\u03c3\u03af\u03bf\u03c5\" (''Apolytirio Gumnasium'', gumnasium school leaving certificate, referred to simply as gymnasium certificate) at HQF ([[National qualifications framework|NQF]]) level 3, which gives automatic admission to the upper secondary education (lyceum). Gymnasium has three academic years of schooling known as \"\u03c4\u03ac\u03be\u03b7\" (grade), numbered 1 through to 3. Ages are typical and can vary with the most common being are between:<ref name=\"Joint Ministerial Decree 79942/\u0393\u03944/2019, Government Gazette 2005 \u0392\u2019/31.5.2019\">{{cite journal|url=https://www.minedu.gov.gr/publications/docs2019/\u03a6\u0395\u039a_2005\u0392_31.05.2019.pdf |title=Joint Ministerial Decree 79942/\u0393\u03944/2019, Government Gazette 2005 \u0392\u2019 / 31.5.2019|publisher=Ministry of Education}}{{in lang|el}} \"Admissions, transfers, studying and organization subjects of schooled life in the secondary education schools\"</ref><ref name=\"School E-Books of Primary, Gymnasium, General Lyceum, EPAL Lyceum\"/>{{ref|d|[C]}}\n\n* 1st Year / First grade (''\u03a0\u03c1\u03ce\u03c4\u03b7 \u03c4\u03ac\u03be\u03b7 \u03b3\u03c5\u03bc\u03bd\u03b1\u03c3\u03af\u03bf\u03c5''), age 12 to 13-year-olds\n* 2nd Year / Second grade (''\u0394\u03b5\u03c5\u03c4\u03ad\u03c1\u03b1 \u03c4\u03ac\u03be\u03b7 \u03b3\u03c5\u03bc\u03bd\u03b1\u03c3\u03af\u03bf\u03c5''), age 13 to 14 \n* 3th Year / Third grade (''\u03a4\u03c1\u03af\u03c4\u03b7 \u03c4\u03ac\u03be\u03b7 \u03b3\u03c5\u03bc\u03bd\u03b1\u03c3\u03af\u03bf\u03c5''), age 14 to 15\n\nThe types of gymnasium in Greece are:\n{{col-begin}}  \n* Gymnasium\n* Evening Gymnasium\n* Ecclesiastical Gymnasium\n* Gymnasium of Cross-Cultural Education\n* Experimental Gymnasium (to enter must pass certain exams on Maths, <br/>Science, Reading Comprehension and Writing - the last two are written as one)\n* Integrated [[Special education|Special]] Vocational Gymnasium-Lyceum (\u0395\u039d.\u0395.\u0395.\u0393\u03a5.-\u039b; 4 years for the gymnasium)\n* Music Gymnasium (to enter this type of school students must pass certain exams on a musical instrument) \n* Art Gymnasium (to enter this type of school students must pass certain exams on either arts, dance, or theater; 2004\u2013Present)\n{{col-end}}\n'''Gymnasium Curriculum''' \n{| border=\"0\"\n|-\n| '''Subjects of Gymnasium'''\n| colspan=\"6\"| '''Weekly Hours of Grades'''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\" \n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | (school year 2019-2020) \n||1st  \n||2nd  \n||3rd  \n|-\n| Modern Greek Language\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n|-\n| Modern Greek Literature\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n|-\n| Ancient Greek Language \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n|-\n| Ancient Greek Literature  \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n|-\n| Mathematics           \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|4\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|4\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|4\n|-\n| Chemistry   \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|- \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1  \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1 \n|-\n| Physics  \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n|-\n| Biology\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n| History\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n|-\n| Art    \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n| Music          \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n| Technology                  \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n| Geography                     \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|-\n|-\n| Home Economics  \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|-\n|-\n| Religious Studies\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n|-\n| Computer Studies \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n| Physical Education  \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n|-\n| Social and Political Studies\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n|-\n| English Language (Modern)      \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2 \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2 \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2  \n|-\n| 2nd Foreign Language (Modern; French or German)                                   \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n|-\n| '''Gymnasium Total Weekly Hours of Grades:'''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|32\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|32 \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|32 \n|}\n\n===Lyceum===\n[[Lyceum]] (\u039b\u03cd\u03ba\u03b5\u03b9\u03bf, ''Lykeio'', Upper Secondary Education School; High School: the US term for secondary school) non-compulsory education 3 years.\n\nAdmitted students can have a maximum age up to 20-year-old, while must have Gymnasium Certificate or Lower Secondary Education School Certificate or its international equivalent. Starts on September 11 and ends on June 15. Lessons end in late May so that the students will be able to study for their examinations in June. The Evening Lyceum (''\u0395\u03c3\u03c0\u03b5\u03c1\u03b9\u03bd\u03cc'') is at both for adult students and underage working students lasts 3 years since 2020\u20132021 academic year.<ref name=\"Law 4547/2018, Government Gazette 102\u0391\u2019/12.06.2018\">{{cite journal|url=https://www.minedu.gov.gr/publications/docs2018/EPAL_N_4547_FEK_102A_12-06-2018.pdf |title=Law 4547/2018, Government Gazette 102\u0391\u2019/12.06.2018|publisher=Ministry of Education}} {{in lang|el}}</ref><ref name=\"Joint Ministerial Decree \u03a62/107972/\u03944, Government Gazette 2636 B\u2019/05.07.2018\">{{cite journal|url=https://www.minedu.gov.gr/publications/docs2018/2018.06_%CE%A5%CE%91_%CE%A9%CE%A0%CE%A3_3%CE%B5%CF%84%CF%8E%CE%BD_%CE%95%CF%83%CF%80%CE%B5%CF%81_%CE%95%CE%A0%CE%91%CE%9B_%CE%BD4386_2016_%CE%A6%CE%95%CE%9A_2636%CE%92_05.07.2018_.pdf#page=11|title=Joint Ministerial Decree \u03a62/107972/\u03944, Government Gazette 2636 B\u2019/05.07.2018|publisher=Ministry of Education}}{{in lang|el}}</ref> After having completed the 3rd grade, the graduates of the Lyceum are awarded the \"\u0391\u03c0\u03bf\u03bb\u03c5\u03c4\u03ae\u03c1\u03b9\u03bf \u039b\u03c5\u03ba\u03b5\u03af\u03bf\u03c5\" qualification (''[[Apolytirion|Apolytirio]] Lykeiou'', Lyceum Apolytirio, upper secondary leaving certificate, high school diploma, referred to simply as lyceum certificate) at HQF([[National qualifications framework|NQF]]) / [[European Qualifications Framework|EQF]] level 4, at [[International Standard Classification of Education|ISCED]] level 3.<ref name=\"International Standard Classification of Education (ISCED) 2011\">{{cite web|url=http://uis.unesco.org/sites/default/files/documents/international-standard-classification-of-education-isced-2011-en.pdf |title=International Standard Classification of Education (ISCED) 2011 |publisher=Unesco Organization}}{{in lang|en}}</ref><ref name=\"ISCED-F 2013 Fields of education and training \u2013 Detailed field descriptions\">{{cite web|url=http://uis.unesco.org/sites/default/files/documents/international-standard-classification-of-education-fields-of-education-and-training-2013-detailed-field-descriptions-2015-en.pdf |title=ISCED-F 2013 Fields of education and training \u2013 Detailed field descriptions |publisher=Unesco Organization}}{{in lang|en}}</ref> The marking scale on the Apolytirio Lykeiou (GPA{{ref|a|[A]}}) is set to a 20-point grading scale.<ref name=\"School E-Books of Primary, Gymnasium, General Lyceum, EPAL Lyceum\"/> The Lyceum Apolytirio is required for admission to Higher Education and to continue studies, and is an equivalent in level to the [[GCE Advanced Level (United Kingdom)|GCE Advanced Level]].<ref name=\"UK University League Teables\">{{cite journal|url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/ng-interactive/2019/jun/07/university-league-tables-2020|title=UK University League Tables|publisher=The Guardian}} By Subject Area, Programme, HEI, Region {{in lang|en}}</ref><ref name=\"International University Degree Equivalents\">{{cite news|url= https://www.grb.uk.com/recruiter-research/international-degree-equivalents |title=International University Degree Equivalents |publisher=Graduate Recruitment Bureau  }} {{in lang|en}}</ref>\n\nStudents wishing to access study programmes in [[Higher education|Higher Education]] must be both secondary education school graduates (lyceum or its equivalent) holding Apolytirio Lykeiou (lyceum certificate or its equivalent) and must take nationally set examinations officially entitled \"\u03a0\u03b1\u03bd\u03b5\u03bb\u03bb\u03b1\u03b4\u03b9\u03ba\u03ad\u03c2 \u0395\u03be\u03b5\u03c4\u03ac\u03c3\u03b5\u03b9\u03c2\" (Pan-Hellenic Examinations, ''Panelladikes Eksetaseis'') which is an externally assessed national standardized test given one time in any given school year, which also accept all adult ages for candidates. Each student is allowed to choose one stream/pathway. Apolytirio certificate grants the right to pursue entry to higher education at a later date by participating at the pan-Hellenic examinations. Ministry of Education bears the responsibility for the central organisation of these matriculation examinations. Candidates exam in 4 subjects that have selected from the 3rd grade of lyceum, while different numerical value titled \"\u03c3\u03c5\u03bd\u03c4\u03b5\u03bb\u03b5\u03c3\u03c4\u03ae\u03c2 \u03b2\u03b1\u03c1\u03cd\u03c4\u03b7\u03c4\u03b1\u03c2\" (coefficient weight) has assigned to each of those subjects contributes differently towards the overall score.\n\nSuccessful admission is determined through the combination of a) \"\u0392\u03b1\u03b8\u03bc\u03cc\u03c2 \u03a0\u03c1\u03cc\u03c3\u03b2\u03b1\u03c3\u03b7\u03c2\", literally \"the access score\", that is the candidate's weighted average of the grades achieved in examinations, b) the candidate's \"\u0392\u03b1\u03b8\u03bc\u03cc\u03c2 \u03a0\u03c1\u03bf\u03b1\u03b3\u03c9\u03b3\u03ae\u03c2 \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u0391\u03c0\u03cc\u03bb\u03c5\u03c3\u03b7\u03c2\" \u0392.\u03a0.\u0391. represents the student's sum of all three Grade Point Averange (GPA) earned in 1st, 2nd, 3rd Grade of lyceum each of these is multiplied by a given coefficient weight where the result is divided by two, \u0392.\u03a0.\u0391. = (1st Grade GPA &times; 0.4 + 2nd Grade GPA &times; 0.7 + 3rd Grade GPA &times; 0.9) / 2, c) the candidate's \"\u03bc\u03b7\u03c7\u03b1\u03bd\u03bf\u03b3\u03c1\u03b1\u03c6\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc \u03b4\u03b5\u03bb\u03c4\u03af\u03bf\" (''michanografiko deltio'', application form) in which it states its preferences for the higher education institutions by priority order, d) the available number of places allocated in each academic department. The number of students that are admitted for each programme is determined annually by the Ministry of Education. As there are usually more applicants than places available in certain fields of study, students with the highest average exam results are selected, e) For admission to programmes requiring specialised knowledge or skills, special admission examinations are require in one or more certain subjects (such as fine arts, architecture, music studies, foreign languages, and others) or compulsory preparatory tests (health, sports, psychometric). \"\u0392\u03b5\u03b2\u03b1\u03af\u03c9\u03c3\u03b7 \u03a0\u03c1\u03cc\u03c3\u03b2\u03b1\u03c3\u03b7\u03c2\" (''Vevaiosi Prosvasis'', Access to Higher Education Certificate) is a document given to students soon after Pan-Hellenic Examinations results are released.\n\nLyceum designates school class levels based on the years of schooling of the student cohort, using 3 academic year levels, known as \"\u03c4\u03ac\u03be\u03b7\" (grade), numbered 1 through to 3. Ages are typical{{ref|d|[C]}} and can vary with the most common being are between:  \n* 1st Year / First grade (''\u03a0\u03c1\u03ce\u03c4\u03b7 \u03c4\u03ac\u03be\u03b7 \u03bb\u03c5\u03ba\u03b5\u03af\u03bf\u03c5''), age 15 to 16-year-olds\n* 2nd Year / Second grade (''\u0394\u03b5\u03c5\u03c4\u03ad\u03c1\u03b1 \u03c4\u03ac\u03be\u03b7 \u03bb\u03c5\u03ba\u03b5\u03af\u03bf\u03c5''), age 16 to 17\n* 3rd Year / Third grade (''\u03a4\u03c1\u03af\u03c4\u03b7 \u03c4\u03ac\u03be\u03b7 \u03bb\u03c5\u03ba\u03b5\u03af\u03bf\u03c5''), age 17 to 18\n\nThe types of lyceum ([[:el:\u039b\u03cd\u03ba\u03b5\u03b9\u03bf|\u039b\u03cd\u03ba\u03b5\u03b9\u03bf]]) in Greece are:\n{{col-begin}}  \n* \u039c\u03bf\u03c5\u03c3\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc \u039b\u03cd\u03ba\u03b5\u03b9\u03bf (''Mousiko Lykeio''; Music Lyceum; 3 years, 1998\u2013Present)<br>(to enter this type of school students must pass certain exams on a musical instrument)\n* \u03a0\u03b5\u03b9\u03c1\u03b1\u03bc\u03b1\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc \u039b\u03cd\u03ba\u03b5\u03b9\u03bf (''Peiramtiko Lykeio''; Experimental Lyceum; 3 years, 1995\u2013Present)<br>(to enter this type of schools students must pass certain exams on Mathematics, Science,<br>Reading Comprehension and Writing [the last two are written as one])\n* \u0393\u03b5\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc \u039b\u03cd\u03ba\u03b5\u03b9\u03bf (\u0393\u0395\u039b; ''Geniko Lykeio''; General Lyceum; 3 years, 1976-1996, 2006\u2013Present)\n* \u0393\u03b5\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc \u039b\u03cd\u03ba\u03b5\u03b9\u03bf \u0394\u03b9\u03b1\u03c0\u03bf\u03bb\u03b9\u03c4\u03b9\u03c3\u03bc\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae\u03c2 \u0395\u03ba\u03c0\u03b1\u03af\u03b4\u03b5\u03c5\u03c3\u03b7\u03c2 (\u0393\u0395\u039b\u0394\u0395; i.e. comprehensive lyceum type; <br>''Diapolitismiko Lykeio''; General Lyceum of Cross-Cultural Education; 3 years, 2018\u2013Present)\n* \u039a\u03b1\u03bb\u03bb\u03b9\u03c4\u03b5\u03c7\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc \u039b\u03cd\u03ba\u03b5\u03b9\u03bf (''Kalitexniko Lykeio''; Art Lyceum; 3 years, 2006\u2013Present)<br>(to enter this type of school students must pass certain exams on either arts, dance, or theater)\n* E\u03c0\u03b1\u03b3\u03b3\u03b5\u03bb\u03bc\u03b1\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc \u039b\u03cd\u03ba\u03b5\u03b9\u03bf (\u0395\u03a0\u0391\u039b; ''Epagelmatiko Lykeio''; Vocational Lyceum; EPAL; 3 years, 2006\u2013Present)\n* \u0395\u03c3\u03c0\u03b5\u03c1\u03b9\u03bd\u03cc \u0395\u03c0\u03b1\u03b3\u03b3\u03b5\u03bb\u03bc\u03b1\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc \u039b\u03cd\u03ba\u03b5\u03b9\u03bf (''Esperino Epagelmatiko Lykeio''; Evening Vocational Lyceum; 3 years)\n* \u0395\u03c3\u03c0\u03b5\u03c1\u03b9\u03bd\u03cc \u0393\u03b5\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc \u039b\u03cd\u03ba\u03b5\u03b9\u03bf (''Esperino Geniko Lykeio''; Evening General Lyceum; 3 years, 1976\u2013Present)\n* \u0393\u03b5\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc \u0395\u03ba\u03ba\u03bb\u03b7\u03c3\u03b9\u03b1\u03c3\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc \u039b\u03cd\u03ba\u03b5\u03b9\u03bf (\u0393\u0395\u0395\u039b; ''Ekklisiastiko Lykeio''; Ecclesiastical General Lyceum; 3 years, 2006\u2013Present)\n* \u0395\u03bd\u03b9\u03b1\u03af\u03bf \u0395\u03b9\u03b4\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc \u0395\u03c0\u03b1\u03b3\u03b3\u03b5\u03bb\u03bc\u03b1\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc \u0393\u03c5\u03bc\u03bd\u03ac\u03c3\u03b9\u03bf-\u039b\u03cd\u03ba\u03b5\u03b9\u03bf (\u0395\u039d.\u0395.\u0395.\u0393\u03a5-\u039b; Integrated [[Special education|Special]] Vocational Gymnasium-Lyceum; 4 years for the lyceum)\n{{col-end}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; display: inline-table;\"   \n| colspan=\"5\"  style=\"background:#eaecf0; font-size:85%;\" | '''Lyceum Timetable''' \n|-style=\"font-size:85%;\"\n! Days\n! Hours\n! Times From - To\n! Duration  \n! Break  \n|- style=\"text-align:left;\"  \n|rowspan=\"8\" |   \n* Monday\n* Tuesday\n* Wednesday\n* Thursday\n* Friday\n|-   \n| 1st \n| 08.15 - 09.00    \n| 45'   \n| 5'     \n|-\n| 2st\n| 09.05 - 09.50  \n| 45'  \n| 10'  \n|-  \n| 3rd  \n| 10.00 - 10.45  \n| 45'  \n| 10'  \n|-  \n| 4th \n| 10.55 - 11.40 \n| 45'   \n| 10'  \n|-  \n| 5th  \n| 11.50 - 12.30 \n| 40'   \n| 5'\n|-  \n| 6th  \n| 12.35 - 13.15 \n| 40'   \n| 5'\n|-  \n| 7th  \n|13.20 - 14.00   \n| 40'   \n| - \n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; display: inline-table; margin:.46em;\"   \n| colspan=\"8\" style=\"background:#eaecf0; font-size:85%;\" | '''Evening Lyceum Timetable'''<ref name=\"Law 4547/2018, Government Gazette 102\u0391\u2019/12.06.2018\"/>\n|-style=\"font-size:85%;\" \n! Days\n! Hours\n! Times From - To\n! Alternate Times From - To \n! Duration  \n! Break  \n|- style=\"text-align:left;\"  \n|rowspan=\"8\" |   \n* Monday\n* Tuesday\n* Wednesday\n* Thursday\n* Friday\n|-   \n| 1st \n| 18.00 - 18.40   \n| 18.30 - 19.10 \n| 40'   \n| -     \n|-\n| 2st\n| 18.40 - 19.20  \n| 19.10 - 19.50\n| 40'  \n| 15'  \n|-  \n| 3rd  \n| 19.35 - 20.15  \n| 20.05 - 20.45\n| 40'  \n| -  \n|-  \n| 4th \n| 20.15 - 20.55 \n| 20.45 - 21.25\n| 40'   \n| 15'  \n|-  \n| 5th  \n| 21.10 - 21:50 \n| 21.40 - 22.20\n| 40'   \n| -\n|-  \n| 6th  \n| 21.50 - 22:30 \n| 22.20 - 23.00\n| 40'   \n| -\n|-  \n| -  \n| -  \n| -\n| -   \n| - \n|}\n\n===General Lyceum (GEL)===\nGeneral Lyceum (GEL; \u0393\u03b5\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc \u039b\u03cd\u03ba\u03b5\u03b9\u03bf; \u0393\u0395.\u039b.; ''Geniko Lykeio'').<ref name=\"Law 4186/2013, Government Gazette 193\u0391\u2019/13.09.2013\">{{cite journal|url=https://www.minedu.gov.gr/publications/docs2018/N_4186_2013_fek193.pdf |title=Law 4186/2013, Government Gazette 193\u0391\u2019/13.09.2013|publisher=Ministry of Education}} {{in lang|el}}</ref><ref name=\"Law 4186/2013, Government Gazette 193\u0391\u2019/13.09.2013 (Note B)\">{{cite journal|url=https://www.hellenicparliament.gr/Nomothetiko-Ergo/Anazitisi-Nomothetikou-Ergou?law_id=638ab1e6-7854-4ce4-89b2-3649a78e2982 |title=Law 4186/2013, Government Gazette 193\u0391\u2019/13.09.2013 (Note B) |publisher=Hellenic Parliament}} {{in lang|el}}</ref><ref name=\"Subjects of Orientation Groups of the General Lyceum, Law 4186/2013\">{{cite journal|url=https://www.hellenicparliament.gr/UserFiles/bcc26661-143b-4f2d-8916-0e0e66ba4c50/a-anaekp-pap.pdf#page=4 |title=Subjects of Orientation Groups of the General Lyceum, Law 4186/2013|publisher=Hellenic Parliament}} {{in lang|el}}</ref>\n\nIt awarded \"\u0391\u03c0\u03bf\u03bb\u03c5\u03c4\u03ae\u03c1\u03b9\u03bf \u0393\u03b5\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03bf\u03cd \u039b\u03c5\u03ba\u03b5\u03af\u03bf\u03c5\" (''Apolytirio Genikou Lykeiou'', General Lyceum Apolytirio, General Lyceum Certificate, Upper Secondary Leaving Certificate, General High School Diploma). The second-grade students must choose one out of the two [[Tracking (education)|academic track]]s named \"\u039f\u03bc\u03ac\u03b4\u03b5\u03c2 \u03a0\u03c1\u03bf\u03c3\u03b1\u03bd\u03b1\u03c4\u03bf\u03bb\u03b9\u03c3\u03bc\u03bf\u03cd\" (Orientation Groups), and the third-grade students one out of the four Orientation Groups. The Orientation Group is also known as Stream or Endorsement which is defined as \"a coherent sequence or series of subjects\". If they wish, graduating students are eligible to exam in Pan-Hellenic Examinations on four subjects of their chosen third-grade Orientation Group. \n \n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"background:transparent;\"\n|+General Lyceum (GEL) National Curriculum 2019-2020\n! rowspan=\"2\" colspan=\"2\" | Subjects \n! colspan=\"3\" | Weekly Hours of Grades\n|-style=\"text-align:center;\" \n! 1st\n! 2nd\n! 3rd\n|-style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" colspan=\"2\"| Modern Greek Language \n| 2  \n| 2  \n| - \n|-\n|-style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" colspan=\"2\"| Modern Greek Literature \n| 2  \n| 2  \n| - \n|-style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" colspan=\"2\" | Ancient Greek Language \n| 5   \n| 2   \n| - \n|-\n|-style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" colspan=\"2\"| Mathematics (Algebra) \n| 2    \n| 2   \n| -\n|-style=\"t